Florida Car Insurance Requirements Explained | PIP, Property Damage & More
1Likes
395Views
Oct 222025
If you drive in Florida, understanding the states minimum auto insurance requirements is essential especially after an accident. Many drivers are surprised to learn that Floridas required coverage is among the lowest in the country. By law, Florida only requires: $10,000 in Personal Injury Protection (PIP) covers your medical expenses and partial lost wages, regardless of fault. $10,000 in Property Damage Liability (PDL) covers damage you cause to someone elses vehicle or property. Thats it. Florida does not require Bodily Injury (BI) liability coverage for most drivers. This means that if youre hit by someone carrying only the state minimum, their insurance may not pay anything toward your medical bills or pain and suffering. To protect yourself, its crucial to have Uninsured/Underinsured Motorist (UM/UIM) coverage. This coverage steps in when the at-fault driver has no insurance or insufficient coverage to pay for your injuries. At Mausner Graham Injury Law, weve seen firsthand how often accident victims face huge medical bills because the at-fault driver carried only minimum coverage. FAQ Section Q1: Whats the minimum auto insurance required in Florida? Florida requires $10,000 in Personal Injury Protection (PIP) and $10,000 in Property Damage Liability (PDL). Q2: Does Florida require Bodily Injury (BI) coverage? No most drivers are not required to carry BI coverage, meaning their policy may not cover injuries to others. Q3: What happens if the at-fault driver doesnt have BI coverage? You can turn to your own Uninsured/Underinsured Motorist (UM) coverage to pay for your medical expenses and losses. Q4: Is the minimum coverage enough? Not usually. Medical bills from even a minor crash can exceed $10,000 quickly, leaving you exposed to out-of-pocket costs. Q5: How can a lawyer help after an accident with an underinsured driver?
